NORMALISED EXTRACT (direct technical content)

1. Definition
The Hamming distance between two equal-length strings or vectors is the number of positions at which corresponding symbols differ. For binary words a and b, HammingDistance(a,b) = popcount(a XOR b).
Time complexity for a linear per-symbol algorithm is O(n) (n = length); space complexity O(1) for streaming comparisons.

2. Binary formula (XOR + popcount)
Compute XOR of the two bit-vectors; the number of 1 bits in the XOR is the Hamming distance. For integers: distance32(x,y) = popcount32(x ^ y); distance64(x,y) = popcount64(x ^ y).

3. String handling and Unicode
JavaScript strings are UTF-16 sequences of code units. Code points above 0xFFFF are encoded as surrogate pairs. Iteration by numeric index visits UTF-16 code units, which may split surrogate pairs; iteration by for...of or String's iterator visits Unicode code points. To compare textual characters for Hamming distance at grapheme or code point level, iterate by code points (for...of or [...str]) and use codePointAt(0) on each element if numeric code is needed.

4. Algorithms and implementations
4.1 Wegner loop (bit-clearing loop)
Procedure: val = x ^ y; count = 0; while (val != 0) { val = val & (val - 1); count++; } Returns number of 1 bits in val. This costs O(k) where k = number of 1 bits (useful when k is small).

4.2 Tree-based popcount (parallel add / pairwise sums)
Use masks and shifts to add bit counts in progressively larger groups:
- m1  = 0x5555555555555555  (0101...)
- m2  = 0x3333333333333333  (00110011...)
- m4  = 0x0f0f0f0f0f0f0f0f  (00001111...)
- m8  = 0x00ff00ff00ff00ff
- m16 = 0x0000ffff0000ffff
- m32 = 0x00000000ffffffff
Algorithm (64-bit):
x = (x & m1) + ((x >> 1) & m1)
x = (x & m2) + ((x >> 2) & m2)
x = (x & m4) + ((x >> 4) & m4)
x = (x & m8) + ((x >> 8) & m8)
x = (x & m16) + ((x >> 16) & m16)
x = (x & m32) + ((x >> 32) & m32)
Return x (contains count) or extract lower bits as needed.

4.3 Multiply-and-shift popcount (Harley-Seal / multiply trick)
After reducing counts to 8-bit lanes, multiply by h01 = 0x0101010101010101 and shift right by 56 to accumulate byte sums into the high byte: result = (x * h01) >> 56.

4.4 Lookup-table popcount
Precompute popcount for 16-bit values in an array wordbits[65536]; popcount32(x) = wordbits[x & 0xFFFF] + wordbits[x >> 16]. Requires memory but gives O(1) per word with 2 reads.

4.5 Compiler intrinsics and hardware popcount
GCC/Clang provide __builtin_popcount(unsigned) and __builtin_popcountll(unsigned long long) which compile to POPCNT hardware instruction when available. C++20 offers std::popcount(unsigned) in <bit>.

4.6 Hamming distance via popcount of XOR
For integers: int hamming_distance(unsigned x, unsigned y) { return popcount(x ^ y); }
For strings of equal length: iterate positions i, increment counter when s1[i] != s2[i]. For Unicode-aware comparisons use code point iteration; lengths must be equal in chosen unit (code units vs code points vs grapheme clusters).

5. JavaScript specifics
5.1 String.prototype.codePointAt(index) signature and behavior
Signature: String.prototype.codePointAt(index) -> non-negative integer or undefined.
Parameters: index coerced to integer; undefined becomes 0. Returns full code point when index addresses a UTF-16 lead surrogate followed by a valid trail surrogate; if index points to a trailing surrogate, returns the trailing surrogate code unit only.
Specification reference: ECMAScript String.prototype.codePointAt.

5.2 Iterating strings by code points
Use for (const ch of str) { ... } or [...str] to iterate by Unicode code points. For each element from the iterator, element.codePointAt(0) yields the numeric code point.

5.3 Bitwise operators behavior
JavaScript bitwise operators coerce operands to signed 32-bit integers. Expressions like a ^ b operate on 32-bit values; for values >32 bits use BigInt and BigInt bit operations. Unsigned right shift >>> coerces to unsigned 32-bit.

5.4 Implementing popcount/hamming in JS
For 32-bit integers: use val = x ^ y | 0 (ensure 32-bit), then apply efficient integer popcount implementations (Wegner loop or tree-based masks). For values that require >32 bits, use BigInt: compute (xBig ^ yBig) and implement popcount on BigInt via repeated x &= x - 1 (works with BigInt) or split into 64-bit chunks and use lookup.

6. Complexity and performance
- Per-symbol string comparison: O(n) time, O(1) space.
- Integer Hamming via popcount: cost proportional to word-size or number of set bits depending on algorithm. Wegner loop cost O(k) where k = popcount; tree/multiply algorithms cost O(log W) arithmetic ops where W = word size; hardware POPCNT executes in constant cycles.

7. Best practices and troubleshooting
- Verify length equality in chosen unit before computing string Hamming distance.
- For Unicode text, decide whether distance should count code points or grapheme clusters; grapheme clusters require libraries (Intl.Segmenter or third-party).
- Prefer compiler intrinsics or hardware popcount for large-scale bit counting.
- In JS, prefer for...of when comparing user-visible characters; avoid index-based loops over UTF-16 if surrogate pairs matter.
- When npm registry pages are required for package-specific API, handle HTTP 403 by using npm CLI or registry API (registry.npmjs.org) for metadata retrieval.

